     `description: (+ "The text_editor control provides a means for editing text based "
                      "buffers, and can either be used for editing local in-memory content or, for "
                      "remote files when the application is served via HTTP.Â  Â The editor can be split "
                      "into multiple views of the same content, provides theming, and color coded "
                      "markup capabilities.Â  Additionally, key sequences can be used either in the "
                      "scope of the editor, or via global scope.Â  It can adapt well to being a "
                      "sub-control, and has a large number of options to enable higher fidelity "
                      "between serialization and deserialization cycles.Â Â  <br><br>#### Example Usage "
                      "<br>```(text_editor \n   { mode: `juno\n     on_change: (function (editor val)\n  "
                      "         (progn\n                      (log (+ (control_name editor) \": change: "
                      "\" val))))\n     name: \"Test Editor\"\n     evaluator_id: (control_id "
                      "*system_repl*)\n     on_initialized: (fn (control)\n                      (notify "
                      "(+ (control_name control) \": initialized!\")))\n   })```<br><br><br>---<br><br> "
                      "This control serves as a wrapper around a third party library, the Ace Editor.Â  "
                      "The control abstracts certain Ace editor functionality as part of the control\'s "
                      "interface. <br><br>#### Ace Editor               <br><br>  The underlying text "
                      "editor library used for this control is the BSD licensed Ace Editor.Â  The "
                      "documentation for this library is available here: "
                      "https://github.com/ajaxorg/ace.Â  Certain underlying functions have been "
                      "elevated and exposed at the top level control interface for purposes of the "
                      "design and implementation of the text_editor control.Â  Direct access to the Ace "
                      "editor instance and its functionality is via the `editor` key in the control\'s "
                      "interface. Since this control uses a third party library underneath, any "
                      "underlying state not captured directly in the controls options object will be "
                      "lost when serialized.Â  A project objective is to build out the interface for "
                      "this control toward a more idiomatic and \"lisp-like\" interface.Â  Â The exposed "
                      "functionality should be expected to be able to save state and restore, unless "
                      "otherwise noted.<br><br>#### Modes               <br><br> The editor can be set "
                      "to operate in a certain \"mode\" state. Changing the editing mode enables certain "
                      "functionalities to be \"turned on\", and which is specifically relevant for the "
                      "type and purpose of the content being edited.Â  There are several modes that are "
                      "prebuilt into the editor: Juno/Lisp, Javascript, CSS, and plain text.Â  Each of "
                      "these modes provide specific features such as syntax highlighting, suggestion "
                      "rules, and active formatting rules.Â <br>Modes can be selected at creation time "
                      "and during run-time.Â  Â  The mode is indicated visually by the \"Current Editing "
                      "Mode\" title bar text, located to the far right on the default title bar.Â  TheÂ  "
                      "`(get_mode)` Â function can be used in the control\'s interface, which is called "
                      "with zero arguments.Â Â Â  <br> The mode can be changed by the user in the "
                      "control\'s command menu, where the user can select via the Set Edit Mode sub "
                      "menu.Â Â  The Controls interface exposes theÂ  `set_mode` Â function, where a "
                      "string that is equal to the mode name is given as an argument.Â  The names of "
                      "the built-in modes are as follows: ```[ `juno `javascript `text `css `json "
                      "]```<br><br> Each element in the array can be used to "
                      "supplyÂ `set_mode`.Â Â <br>Additional modes can be constructed and made available "
                      "to the environment that then can be utilized by the text_editor "
                      "control.Â Presently, the only custom mode isÂ `juno`, which calls back into the "
                      "Lisp environment for context.Â  Â The other modes are standard ACE editor modes "
                      "for their respective content type.Â  In this environments file structure, mode "
                      "files are found namedÂ `js_lib/mode-*`, where all relevant mode-code is found "
                      "with the \"mode-\" prefix.Â  Â <br>Mode details can be found on the Ace website, "
                      "https://ace.c9.io/.Â Â <br><br>#### Split Panels            <br><br>Editors can "
                      "be split into multiple views of the same content.Â  Changes to the content are "
                      "propagated to each view, which is linked to the same content.Â  This means that "
                      "all changes in one will be reflected in the other editor.Â  Cursor positions and "
                      "display area can be independent to allow for simultaneous editing of a single "
                      "file in multiple panels.Â  Â The mechanism by which this occurs is a shared "
                      "underlying AceÂ  `Session`Â  instance.Â  There are some special characteristics of "
                      "the multi-pane mode.<br>When there are multiple panels open to the same editor, "
                      "and one of the editor panels is hidden, it will not be stored in the holding "
                      "tank, and will be disposed.Â  Like other controls, when there is only one "
                      "instance open, the control will behave in the standard form.Â  When hidden, the "
                      "control will be stored, not destroyed.Â Â <br>Additionally, in the multiple-panel "
                      "mode, if the buffer is unsaved, the closing control will not ask if you want to "
                      "save the content, but will instead close.Â  Once the final view into the content "
                      "is reached, and the editor contained unsaved material, the user will be "
                      "prompted if they want to save or store the contents of the editor.<br>The "
                      "interface commandÂ `split_window`Â allows for programmatic control over this "
                      "functionality.Â Â <br><br>### Launch Options                 <br><br>Options "
                      "provided to the function allow for modification of behaviors and specific "
                      "functionality to be enabled or disabled at the time of the controls creation.Â  "
                      "Â The anything placed in the options object will be serialized when the "
                      "environment is saved, and so it is important to make sure that values must be "
                      "able to represent themselves in JSON form.Â  Â <br>clone_with_editor_id:string "
                      "-When present, the created editor instance will share an editing session with "
                      "the editor with the given id.Â Â The given editor must be a text_editor "
                      "control.Â Â  <br>mode:string -Specifies which mode the editor should start in.Â  "
                      "For this to take effect, the mode must be a defined Ace editor mode (see Modes "
                      "above).Â  If not provided, the mode is determined by the filename if "
                      "possible.<br>on_mode_set:function -If present, this function is called with the "
                      "modeÂ `(on_mode_set mode_name)`Â when the mode is changed.Â <br>on_save:function "
                      "-Called after a document has been saved successfully.Â  Since an edit session "
                      "can be shared between multiple controls that display different views, saving is "
                      "handled in a centralized way through a shared function, theÂ  "
                      "`save_event_handler` function.Â  This external function receives a request and "
                      "then alerts all the editor with the same `basename`, which is set in the "
                      "options object by the control by calling their `save_complete` functions.Â  If "
                      "the editor has an `on_save` function in the options, then that function will be "
